Right. And how do you think that "turning down the music" happens? By the way, you're talking about limiting, not compressing, so let's clarify that before moving forward. When a limiter sees that the signal is too loud, as long as we're talking about digital limiters, it'll turn it down, but it won't turn down the quiet parts, so the proportion changes. You can't undo an "overcompressed" mix by turning down the volume, it doesn't work like that, the new narrow dynamic range has been baked into the audio and the formerly loud parts will be too quiet.

Listened to the first three tracks. Love it so far, it has a consistent and very impressive mix of acoustic and processed sounds that manage to give a great amount of interesting textures, but at the same time thru a cohesive and enjoyable progression. At times it reminds of some of the more experimental sections of PIL's Flowers of Romance or La Monte Young. >>114265243
Not bad. The vocal and instrument performance is nothing but amazing, remind quite of Jonny Craig's era DGD, but there are quite a few that in my opinion that kind of damage the listening. The mixing sounds very compressed, a more cleaner mix and some mastering would help the song sound more refined. The breakdown are badly placed around the song in my opinion, we have one just starting the song and breaking the flow out of nowhere. That's not bad in itself, that's what breakdowns do, but there's barely enough progress in the song to throw a breakdown in, those generally go in the parts with more tension, it sounds random even. Hopefully my feedback gave you some worthy advice.

>>114260584
I've been producing since December 2013 and I wouldn't describe myself as "good" at all, and I'm certainly not bored. I would say I know how to do this skill to a satisfactory level that never stops having room for improvement, as the world of music is infinite. Changing DAWs seems utterly pointless, since it is just slowing down the process of getting the exact same end product. Anyone feeling bored/plateaud should pick an important skill and really develop it. For me, it was singing. Being able to sing opened some doors for me, because I now had the option to record myself anytime whenever something popped into my head, and then recreate it later. Another important thing is to be able to play the piano to some degree so you can learn to play different kinds of music and incorporate their composition style into your own to just the right extent that you create something new and exciting to work on.

I think you should try to meet people where they are. When you make chords you probably mostly use diatonic triads of the 12 tone equal temperament system in common cadences and voicings, just like everyone else. There are ways to subvert norms and cliches and introduce people to other sounds, but it doesn't involve wholesale avoidance of those norms. You can more effectively introduce people to the sounds you want them to hear by offering them music that is 80% the sounds they are used to and 20% other sounds you want them to hear. Then mix that resulting sound with 20% other sounds you want people to hear. And so on and so forth.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
In regards to mixing, the foundation is sound selection. Especially your kick and bass need to work together. I've lost hours trying to get my kick sound good with EQ, sidechaining, compressing... but all I needed to do is simply choose another kick with a better transient. 80% of your "mixing" should be the volume fader. If you get sounds work together by simply adjusting the volume fader you need to decide which sound you should replace. If your kick cuts through the bass without any processing you have chosen the right one. The processing itself takes it from 8/10 to 10/10.

Drum sounds are repetitive as fuck, especially when you listen to the current trap rap and drill music. It's like all producers are sharing the same 5 drum kits. Creating your own is part of establishing your own style. Those drums sounds could be based on commonly used sounds but with your personal processing. You created a great snare for one of your tracks? Save it. Layered a great kick? Save it. This is how you end up with your personal drum kit, that sounds like you. My drum sounds are all my own, but it took me years to create my own library sampling real drum sounds from old records. I am currently sampling some 70s Russian progressive rock record that I would like to use for deep house.

>>114275080
>what's A B C D E F G retard?
The A natural minor but that doesnt matter. We now use C major as the main scale.
Boethe made the first note-to-letter notation in the 6th century, starting with A for his lowest arbitrary note.
Fast forward 400 years, and the lowest main organ pipe is C and not A (A is too low and the pipe length is harder to get right). So when writing music for a church organ you'd tune to "boethian C" instead of A.
When Guido de Arezzo 'invented' solfege, he did it based on a common hymn used for "voice tuning". It started with C and went all the way up a 7 note scale. He gave these notes names based on the start of each stanza of the song. He's also one of the main guys behind modern musical notation so his naming of notes was used for most classical instruments, including piano, in most of Europe, which made most european music.
Americans use letter notation instead of solfege so now your piano has a "center C" instead of a "center Do".
As to why we use Cmaj as the most commonly used scale, no real reason. People just like the sound. If you start using Amin you can have A instead of C.

tl;dr solfege

>>114274412
Chart topping popular music has gotten measurably more formulaic musically, as well in terms of production and sonic qualities (the synths and drum beats all sound the same for example). This is because studios have a better idea of what will be successful with mainstream audiences due to superior market research; but also because streaming has made music less profitable overall, there is less room to take risks by allowing artists to experiment. Talented singing and musicianship are also much less relevant in the mainstream due to the electronicisation of music, and pitch correction techniques.

Lots of posters on this board claim that indie music is experiencing something similar, and lots of people shit on more 'artsy' current acts like black midi or king gizzard or something. I don't think thats the same phenomenon as mainstrean music's decline however.

It's funny because when the power disparity between the 'West' and China became obvious Chinese musicians started seeing their own musical traditions as being inferior and therefore imported Western harmonic practice into their own music
When you listen to 'traditional Chinese music' today it likely employs Western harmonic practice when in the past harmony was entirely absent
The Chinese were actually enthusiastic about this

After the fall of the Ottoman empire, there was a 'modernisation' project that was launched which was essentially trying to make Turkey a European country
Ottoman classical music had it's own theory in makam and usul but it didn't use harmony, furthermore it used quarter tones in it's music
The modernisers of the day saw this as being incredibly backwards and so they banned Ottoman classical music being played and constantly broadcast Western classical music in the hope that people would stop using quarter tones in their music and would adopt Western harmonic practice

>>114244763
It's harder than it seems (and it does seem difficult) to get longer/progressive tracks to work in video games. They tend to be hilariously distracting and immersion-breaking whenever there is blatant mismatch with the action or, most insidiously, the lack thereof. At that point you have to design the game around the music rather than the other way around.
Moreover, the prog influence was already fizzling out by the time it was just barely feasible in terms of technical limitations and design repertoire to have a 10+ minute game event that remains interesting throughout.
